<li id="cite_note-84"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-84">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1215172403"><cite id="CITEREFCranney2019" class="citation journal cs1">Cranney, Stephen (2019). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://byustudies.byu.edu/content/next-mormons-how-millennials-are-changing-lds-church">"The Next Mormons: How Millennials Are Changing the LDS Church"</a>. <i>BYU Studies</i>. <b>58</b> (2): 177. <q>Enter the Next Mormons Survey. Riess and Knoll are to be commended for their landmark survey and study that fill the need for a large, representative Latter-day Saint sample.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=BYU+Studies&amp;rft.atitle=The+Next+Mormons%3A+How+Millennials+Are+Changing+the+LDS+Church&amp;rft.volume=58&amp;rft.issue=2&amp;rft.pages=177&amp;rft.date=2019&amp;rft.aulast=Cranney&amp;rft.aufirst=Stephen&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbyustudies.byu.edu%2Fcontent%2Fnext-mormons-how-millennials-are-changing-lds-church&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ABlack+people+and+temple+and+priesthood+policies+in+the+Church+of+Jesus+Christ+of+Latter-day+Saints" class="Z3988"></span></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-85"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-85">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1215172403"><cite id="CITEREFRiess2018" class="citation news cs1">Riess, Jana (June 11, 2018). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.sltrib.com/religion/2018/06/11/commentary-most-mormons-still-believe-the-racist-priesthoodtemple-ban-was-gods-will-survey-shows/">"Commentary: Most Mormons still believe the racist priesthood/temple ban was God's will, survey shows"</a>. <i>The Salt Lake Tribune</i>. <q>The 2016 Next Mormons Survey asked whether respondents felt that the ban on members of African descent was 'inspired of God and was God's will for the church until 1978.' Respondents were given a five-point scale of possible responses, with the upshot being that nearly two-thirds of self-identified Latter-day Saints say they either know (37 percent) or believe (25.5 percent) that the ban was God's will.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=The+Salt+Lake+Tribune&amp;rft.atitle=Commentary%3A+Most+Mormons+still+believe+the+racist+priesthood%2Ftemple+ban+was+God%27s+will%2C+survey+shows&amp;rft.date=2018-06-11&amp;rft.aulast=Riess&amp;rft.aufirst=Jana&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.sltrib.com%2Freligion%2F2018%2F06%2F11%2Fcommentary-most-mormons-still-believe-the-racist-priesthoodtemple-ban-was-gods-will-survey-shows%2F&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ABlack+people+and+temple+and+priesthood+policies+in+the+Church+of+Jesus+Christ+of+Latter-day+Saints" class="Z3988"></span></span>
